This is a good place to be careful, because we know some things about the Andean knot system and some things remain debated.

The quipu (also spelled khipu) used by the Inca Empire consisted of cords, knots, colors, spacing, ply direction, and attachment patterns. It was definitely used for accounting, census data, and administration. Whether some quipus encoded full narrative language is still an open research question—there is intriguing evidence, but no scholarly consensus.

