A speculative synthesis

If you wanted to borrow the principle of quipu rather than imitate it, you might define a Semantic Quipu.

Each concept would be a knot with multiple strands:

* Core invariant (what must stay true)
* Evidence (why it’s believed)
* Relationships (what it’s connects to)
* Transformations (what representations preserve it)
* History (how it developed)
* Confidence (how certain we are)
* Applications (where it’s useful)

The “reading” of the knot wouldn’t depend on a single string of words. It would emerge from traversing those intertwined strands.

Ironically, that circles back to one of your earliest observations:

“A color is a knot.”

The quipu suggests a broader version:

A concept may be understood not as a symbol, but as a structured bundle of relationships whose identity survives many different ways of being tied.

Whether that becomes a useful computational framework depends on whether you can define operations on those bundles that consistently improve retrieval, translation, reasoning, or learning. That’s the point where it stops being just an evocative metaphor and starts becoming an engineering architecture.